04559nam a22005175i 9780822391753DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20102010ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223917537 a10.1515/97808223917532doi  a(DE-B1597)553063  a(OCoLC)1202624427  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aHIS0250002bisacsh04a972.082221 aPiccato, Pablo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Tyranny of Opinion :bHonor in the Construction of the Mexican Public Sphere /cPablo Piccato. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (400 p.) :b24 illustrations, 7 tables, 1 figure  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Honor and the Public Sphere in the Republican Era -- tPart I. Travails of opinion -- t1. Setting the Rules of Freedom: The Trajectory of the Press Jury -- t2. Representing Public Opinion: Combat Journalists and the Business of Honor -- tPart II. Tumultuous Opinion -- t3. ‘‘The Word of My Conscience’’: Eloquence and the Foreign Debt -- t4. Breaking Lamps and Expanding the Public Sphere: Students and Populacho against the Deuda Inglesa -- tPart III. Taming Opinion -- t5. Honor and the State: Reputation as a Juridical Good -- t6. ‘‘A Horrible Web of Insults’’: The Everyday Defense of Honor -- t7. ‘‘One Does Not Talk to the Dead’’: The Romero-Verástegui A√air and the Apogee of Dueling in Mexico -- tConclusions -- tNotes -- tSources Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the mid-to-late nineteenth century, as Mexico emerged out of decades of civil war and foreign invasion, a modern notion of honor—of one’s reputation and self-worth—became the keystone in the construction of public culture. Mexicans gave great symbolic, social, and material value to honor. Only honorable men could speak in the name of the public. Honor earned these men, and a few women, support and credit, and gave civilian politicians a claim to authority after an era dominated by military heroism.Tracing how notions of honor changed in nineteenth-century Mexico, Pablo Piccato examines legislation, journalism, parliamentary debates, criminal defamation cases, personal stories, urban protests, and the rise and decline of dueling in the 1890s. He highlights the centrality of notions of honor to debates over the nature of Mexican liberalism, describing how honor helped to define the boundaries between public and private life; balance competing claims of free speech, public opinion, and the protection of individual reputations; and motivate politicians, writers, and other men to enter public life. As Piccato explains, under the authoritarian rule of Porfirio Díaz, the state became more active in the protection of individual reputations. It implemented new restrictions on the press. This did not prevent people from all walks of life from defending their honor and reputations, whether in court or through violence. The Tyranny of Opinion is a major contribution to a new understanding of Mexican political history and the evolution of Mexican civil society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aHonorxPolitical aspectszMexico. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Mexico.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822391753zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822391753423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822391753/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHA